### Key Learnings :
- Time Complexity measures how runtime grows with input size.
- We focus on the worst-case scenario using Big O notation.
- O(log n) algorithms are generally faster than O(n).

### Three Rules while calculating time complexity of any Program:
- Always Compute complexity in terms of worst case Scenerio
- Avoid Constants
- Avoid Lower Values

# Time Complexity

## Common Complexities

| Complexity | Example |
|------------|----------|
| O(1) | Array access |
| O(log n) | Binary Search |
| O(n) | Linear Search |
| O(n²) | Nested Loops |

## Important Rules

1. Drop constants
   O(2n) → O(n)

2. Keep dominant term
   O(n² + n) → O(n²)

3. Nested loops multiply
   O(n × n) = O(n²)

### Space Complexity:
- It is the Memory Space
-  Space Complexity  = Auxilliary Space + Input Space

- Auxilliary Space : Space that you take to solve the problem
   E.g. int a, b
    C = a + b  (here C is the Auxilliary Space)

- Input Space : The space that you take to store the input. 
    E.g. int a, b  (here a and b are Input Space)

